
[1]orthodoxy

   OR'THODOXY, n. [Gr. right, true, and opinion, from to think.]

   1. Soundness of faith; a belief in the genuine doctrines taught in the
   Scriptures.

   Basil bears full and clear testimony to Gregory's orthodoxy.

   2. Consonance to genuine scriptural doctrines; as the orthodoxy of a
   creed.
